    &lt;Title&gt;Lack of compassion - urgent care&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;Visited urgent care with my partner with a possibly life threatening condition. 
As a staff nurse myself I never once thought a fellow nurse could be so rude and unwelcoming. 
My partner arrived first and informed me that the triage nurse was quite rough when assessing him and very stern, abrupt manner - this shocked me! 
He did not understand what was happening so I wanted to ask for an update from the triage nurse. 
I went to reception initially and the nurse was sat in a office next to reception so could hear my question and the receptionist went and had to repeat my question (even though the nurse was sat with the door open - she was clearly disinterested) and answered the receptionist rudely and did not look or speak directly to me! 
I then informed her I was merely asking for an update and her response was so rude and lacked compassion and empathy - just responded as if I was a nuisance! 
Could not believe a nurse (she had a sisters uniform on) would communicate in that manner - hardly any explanation at all. 
We got transferred to Preston and when we left she never came and said goodbye, good luck - nothing. 
I love Chorley hospital normally but I would definitely not want to be seen by that particular nurse again - she definitely needs reminding of why she came to be a nurse and implement the 6 Câ€™s of nursing within her role&lt;/CommentText&gt;
